<DOC><DOCNO> AP890523-0063 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 0940EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-VernonSavings     05-23 0270</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Vernon Savings,0279</SECOND><HEAD>Former Thrift Executive Agrees To Plead Guilty in Fraud Case</HEAD><DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A former savings and loan executive has agreed toplead guilty to federal charges he took part in a scheme to donatethrift funds to House Speaker Jim Wright and other politicians,court records show.   Federal law forbids corporate contributions to politicians.   Pat L. Malone, former executive vice president of VernonSavings, admitted setting up a system that used thrift funds toreimburse Vernon employees for making $55,000 in politicalcontributions in 1986, according to a criminal information filed infederal court.   The documents show Malone agreed to plead guilty to bank fraudcharges.   Court records show donations included unspecified contributionsto Wright and $2,000 to 1986 Texas Tribute, a political committeeset up to seek donations for the Texas Democrat.   Court records show other contributions included $2,000 to Sen.Jake Garn, R-Utah; $1,000 to Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.; $3,000to the gubernatorial campaign of former Rep. Tom Loeffler of Texas,and unspecified contributions to Rep. Bill Lowrey, D-Calif., andformer Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y.   Federal regulators closed Vernon in 1987. It reopened asMontfort Savings Association, then was sold in December and renamedFirst Gibraltar Federal Savings Bank.   There was no answer today at a Dallas telephone listing in thename of a Pat Malone.   The criminal information accused Malone of soliciting politicalcontributions from Vernon officers and having them file falseexpense vouchers to reimburse themselves for the donations.   A criminal information is filed in place of an indictment toshow charges to which a defendant has agreed to plead guilty.</TEXT></DOC>